description.text:
V3/4 cuts some unneeded material out to save a little weight/plastic/print time, it also addes the option to print a pair of holders so you can use extruders other than the MP V9/10 (Gregs Wade for instance)(note - This will only work with groove mount or other hot ends that don't require the 30mm retaining strap). V2 adds some chamfers and a retained nut for the belt clamp so the pillar does not foul on the Z lead screws Yet another X Carriage for the Orca V0.3. This one is fully agnostic as to what type of timing belt you use as the belt is retained by straps. This design uses 3 of my LM8UU bearing carries and 2 of the straps from my Y belt tensioner. The extruder base and the bearing carriers are all retained by captured nylock nuts. The advantages of this design (I think) are
Use any type of timing belt (small enough)
Belt clamp is a simple design
Belt is attached to the double bearing side
The extruder motor is placed to the back (assuming like me you want all the other motors at the front)
You do not loose any Z height, by adjusting the car_thickness parameter in the SCAD file you can gain Z height

Download the individual files or the zip file, If you want the OpenSCAD file to render the sketch as shown in the images then you need the zip file. The zip file contains the Orca dxf's and timing belt library, you will also need MCAD library to render the sketch, the carriage should compile without external libraries though. Print the X carriage, 3 LM8UU bearing holders, 2 belt straps You will need the following vitamins 12 - M4 Nylock nuts
6 â€“ M4 x 30 (32 would be better) cap screws
16 - M4 Washers

description.text: Puzzle piece

I built this "mini" RC blimp from one of those micro RC cars that used to be all the rage. It putters around my large living room with a slow lumbering grace and it is perfect for those who hate trying to fly those cheap little helicopters indoors. The total cost for this project is under $20 (with a free trial of amazon prime). I bought the car from amazon, frame 2 is modeled specifically for this car, the other parts should be compatible with the standard motor. This build is based on this instructable, except with printed parts for an easier and better construction.
http://www.instructables.com/id/13-RC-Blimp

First, I purchased this micro RC car from amazon.
http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B008MDTBXO I also purchased this vibrator motor from my local radio shack and removed the counterweight.
http://www.radioshack.com/product/index.jsp?productId=2914700 The parts are printed with full infill of course. The shaft hole for the propeller will likely get filled in. I heated up a needle with a lighter and poked it through. The printed propellers work fine, but I'm sure they could be replaced with superior purchased ones. In taking apart the car, I cut off the lights and the steering coil, and soldered the steering motor in place of the coil. The circuit board should snap right into frame 2, along with the battery. Frame 2 is superglued to frame 1, and the switch and charging port are superglued to frame 2. A large straw is used to connect the steering motor frame 3 to frame 1. I also used straws cut in half and stuck to the tape that holds the balloons together for ballast adjustment. See the instructable for other details on the build.

This is a remix of three different "things" to form a new Sleigh combination.
The sleigh was made more easily printable by separating the runners. The reindeer were resized from another "thing". The Santa was extracted from a third "thing" and sized to fit the sleigh. I've also posted some further detail on this item on my blog: http://numbersixreprap.blogspot.ie/2013/12/santa-sleighho-ho-ho.html Print, assemble, decorate and enjoy. Don't forget the Instruction tab here also. Regards,

Download, slice, print and assemble. The components are supplied individually and in groups.
Reindeer: If your print bed is nice and level and has the area you can print the six reindeer and supporting bar in one go. The dear work well sliced at .3mm and 25% fill. Sleigh: The sleigh body prints best on it's side (as supplied), with support enabled. Again, .3mm, with 20% fill or even less works. Santa: Santa prints well hollow or any low fill %. He does need support enabled though to support his arms and hat as it prints. I used Cura to print Santa with good results, using an advanced setting to sit him 2mm below the base giving a flat bottom to sit on. Sleigh Runners (sides): There's a left and right side because the lower section is narrower. Examine the sliced gcode in some previewer to ensure adequate infill between the narrow swirls. Print the first layer slowly so the narrow swirls take well to the print bed. Assembly tips: Removed the support material from the sleigh body, and the little hole in the front of the body. Remove and clean any plastic flashing or blips from the inside of runners (sides) where they push on to the sleigh body. Test fit without glue first, then sit one side (runner) flat on a protected surface, dab some glue around the edge of the of the sleigh and push the sleigh into the side. If you want the body recessed from the side then cut a small piece of card to act as a spacer. Repeat for the other side of the sleigh. If the bars are a good fit for the square hole in the reindeer then no glue may be needed. If it's a bit loose then a dab of glue will secure. The bar with reindeer attached just pushes into the square hole in the front of the sleigh. Glue in place if loose. Glue Santa into the sleigh if desired.
Some more detail on my blog:

I printed this illuminated sight because I was searching for a low budget, light weight and cheap night sight for quite some time but didn't find one. A red dot is too chunky for a handgun in my opinion and light is illegal in my country and draws attention to the shooter. This sight is basically a light stick holder that goes behind the normal front sight of the gun and works like tritium night sights but at a much lower price and without the danger of radiation (which is minuscle anyway). I did not design a rear sight because I don't need one myself and didn't want to replace my original rear sight. Also in many guns the rear sight is adjustable. Therefore its bad to replace it. If you wonder about the problem, that there is an illuminated dot at the front of your gun with this sight that draws "enemy" attention there is an easy solution for that:
Put a ball of duct tape in the front tube of the sight after inserting the glow stick but don't print it closed or glue it closed because otherwise you can't remove the glow stick anymore and need to replace the whole sight after it is used up. If you don't like the faint glow the sight emits to the side print it either out of black ABS or spray paint it. Smoothening the sight with sand paper and adding filler and spray paint to it is recommended if you mount it to a real gun, because otherwise it looks pretty crappy and cheap. Post processing: After printing the sight I drilled its hole to 4,5mm and sanded its floor plate to have an even surface to glue it to the gun and to be able to insert the glow stick easily. Fastening: I glued the sight to the gun with superglue. Double sided adhesive tape might work, too. But I doubt it will hold out on a real gun or after several shots. Heat can also be a problem. Compatibillity: This sight works with any normal green glow stick with a size of 4mm x 4mm x 39mm. They last for about 6 to 12 hours and can be bought at fishing stores. Legallity: This sight is completely legal in Germany as far as i know.

title: Stand for Weller WMRP Soldering Pencil

description.text: Like the WMRT SMD desoldering tweezers, the Weller WMRP pencil is a superb, German-made soldering tool. And like the WMRT, the holder that Weller sells is insanely overpriced and a good one can be printed for pennies (see http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:143780 for a WMRT stand). Both tools feature a magnetic switch in the handle which turns off the heat to the tip(s) to preserve tip life; when removed from the holder the tip heats to the preset temperature in just a few seconds. This Thing features a recess for a 12.4mm x 5.5mm ceramic magnet; the sensor is quite sensitive so you don't need a fancy rare earth magnet. The holder is designed to screw onto a heavy base so it won't get knocked over (I used a scrap of 3/4" MDF and some stick-on rubber feet) and features a slide-lock so that the pencil can't be knocked out of the holder accidentally. It drops in and slides downward to lock - see the video here: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NOJmKYtiqRE&feature=youtu.be The design can be edited on Tinkercad at https://tinkercad.com/things/dhjEEe5g69q-wmrp-pencil-stand.

description.text:
After getting TPE from orbi tech, I struggled a bit getting this to print, because the filament just wouldn't stick. Managed to print it on upside-down tape. The cable tie itself works quite well. You can get the "light" version through the hole quite easily, with good enough stability. The "tight" version has a stronger fit, but requires some force to get through the hole. But so far, the TPE didn't rip, you can really stress it. Also there is a small and a big one. Probably this will work with soft PLA or other very flexible materials as well. Light: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=haCL_si94uU
Tight: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sJGGzSqPAFI

Update:
Today I got white NinjFlex, so i tried to print with this. The stickiness is really great, so great even, that it ripped my Kapton tape. So I'm printing just on glass now (but here at 40°C).
The light versions are not really suitable for this material, as it is more flexible and doesn't hold that well. The tight versions are quite good (see photo with white cable tie). Maybe I will even make a tighter version specifically for NinjaFlex. Also it seems like a bit of retraction (1mm) is working for this material, didn't have any problems with the filament getting bent in the extruder yet.

The .pk2 files can be edited to change dimensions or add your initials or logo or whatnot. As i am not familiar with OpenSCAD, i cant make this customizable.
With the TPE from orbi tech, 1.2mm thickness is about the best compromise between usability and stability. Thicker makes it very hard to get through the holes (especially backwards), thinner is likely to break faster and doesn't hold as strong . So it's best if you just scale in x and y direction.
I imagine if you use NinjaFlex or similar filament, you can make it thicker, beacause you can "stretch it through".
Soft PLA might break sooner.
Below is my Slic3r config for the TPE print of the cable-ties
Please inform me, if you print in another material, cheers!

Update:
The setting for NinjaFlex are essentially the same, except for the retraction of 1mm. Also I was able to print with 40mm/s so far with no problems.

comments.text: What temperature for the extruder and bed are you using on the TPE from orbi tech?
comments.author: syakely

comments.text:
I usually control the temperature manually, because of changing surroundings, infill, print speed etc. What TPE are you talking about?
As you probably know, it is difficult to transfer the settings for one set-up to another, due to different extruder materials, environments and whatnot.
I ended up with no heatbed active and got the best results for NinjaFlex around 220°C extruder temp and OrbiTec 210 °C.
Beware that NinjaFlex is sticking like hell, so you may not be able to remove it from the kapton tape or whatever you use. Most things i just printed on glass, except things with a small footprint.
The OrbiTec TPE is quite the opposite, it sticks nowhere except on double sided tape. So I bought technicoll 9220, which is a quite strong permanent adhesive. This worked quite well.

remixed_from.title: Parametric Herringbone Gear Set for Stepper Extruders

description.text:
Having built a half-dozen MPCNCs or so, I borrowed from that experience to build a camera slider at the suggestion of my son-in-law... the result, MPCamSlider. I first tried using the entire Z-axis lead-screw assembly from MPCNC... it worked but turned out too slow and noisy for my liking. I converted it over to belt-drive, mixing/mashing up motor- and idler-mounts for the conversion and preserving the conduit spacing from MPCNC's Z-axis assembly. The C-XYZ and C-spacer parts from MPCNC were used then to make a trolley and a custom plate whipped up to add a platform and help tie the trolley roller assemblies together. The overall length of travel can of course be made to suit... I ended up with 32"-33" of linear travel on the prototype.

The trolley has a small turntable affixed to the top for a rotation axis. I was originally inspired by the Brainy-bits camera slider tutorials and slider mechanism (https://brainy-bits.com/tutorials/control-2-stepper-motors-using-the-arduino-serial-monitor/)... and was taken by the similarity to Greg's Wade extruder gears for the rotating platform. Only larger! So I found a customizable OpenSCAD design for the herringbone gear set that was almost perfect using the defaults and printed/installed them on the trolley platform. A camera mount base was fashioned to match the hole pattern in the large gear and a previously built cell-phone camera holder affixed to the mounting base.

A common fence slat is used as a mounting base for the entire camera slider... and is needed for strength and to keep the entire mechanism from twisting. A couple of 2" x 4" blocks are cut to fit and the 3/4" EMT conduit fastened with suitable clamps and utility screws.

An Arduino Uno and custom sketch are used to control the camera slider in any of several modes of operation. A4988 stepper motor drivers are used to power the stepper motors on both axis and are set for 1/16 micro-stepping. The belt-drive motor gear is a printed GT2 36-tooth gear with 5mm shaft bore. An IR receiver is also connected to the Arduino... allowing complete control of all CamSlider functions with almost any common TV remote. Start and end setpoints are captured, previewed, user-adjusted for speed in both axis, and then run.

Arduino to A4988 connections are described here (https://www.pololu.com/product/1182) with 1/16 stepping and using the 36-tooth GT2 drive gear. Arduino pins 3,4 connect to X-axis A4988 STEP and DIR pins, respectively. Arduino pins 6,7 connect to Z-axis A4988 STEP and DIR pins, respectively.

The Arduino sketch to control the MPCamSlider has now been made available in Thing Files. The code is fairly heavily commented and instructions are included in the header for identifying codes for a different remote, modding the code, and operating the camera slider.

To see the MPCamSlider in action:

Testing the basic 2-axis camera slider
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iHw4fDvjaLw

Camera runs with both TRANSLATE and ROTATE axis moving simultaneously
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f5eP6A_XUgc&t=31s
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fe12ZOdBEGI

Camera run with TRANSLATE-only... translation, no rotation
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KJvaZoEaAXM

Camera run with ROTATE-only... rotation, no translation
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dPlxfGeeGEQ

I have a lengthy -- but incredibly interesting -- thread over in the FliteTest forum that has become quite eclectic in its content. This was a side-project that developed out of nowhere. If interested, the development of the camera slider starts about here...

http://forum.flitetest.com/showthread.php?24251-Cutting-foam-sheets-with-a-needle!&p=315967&viewfull=1#post315967

description.text:
See the back story for more info on what led up to this thing's design.

Menorah designed to be easily wired and worked with 5mm LEDs. The back is open for ease of wiring, and the candle locations are sized for the mounting flanges on 5mm LEDs. The base has mounting pegs for a Raspberry Pi Zero (use M2.5x5mm screws) although it looks like we may wind up using an Arduino.

Initial print ran into issues when filament got tangled up so the early photos show an incomplete print. Photos also show an earlier design which seemed a bit too weak in the support between the base and the menorah body. Will update as we redesign/reprint.

Well, I designed the thing for 5mm LEDs, and Sam went and got 10mm gumdrops for another project, and liked them so much he is wiring it up with those. Still looks pretty cool, though.

Designed so it can be printed laying down on the build plate.

Support is necessary, especially for the front of the base.

Infill is really only relevant to the top of the base. so doesn't have to be too dense.

Back story

I've been printing a bunch of things for coworkers. One in particular - Sam - has been doing a bunch of work with LEDs, so we've been working together on several projects, especially with the upcoming holidays. We worked together to create a version of the Christmas Story leg lamp that was adjusted for use with LEDs (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1978458) and he also wanted a menorah. We found http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:604228 and I printed it scaled down to fit the 5mm LEDs and printed it hollow so he could run wiring inside it, but he found the sharp angles of that design to be too tough to work with... plus he was unable to use a common ground.

We discussed how to go about making a better version from scratch, keeping his design objectives in mind from the get go. I kept the back open for easy wiring, and kept the main connector horizontal so he could use a common ground wire. Tabs keep the wires from popping out too easily.

This is a work in progress and still hasn't been wired so no doubt adjustments will be made.

This is a remix of the Wilson II printer, to convert it to using 8mm rods and bearings. I've also added ziptie channels to the X-Carriage.

The Z Top and Motor files should be mirrored, your slicer should be able to do that.

You will need all the other files from the Wilson II - this is just the files I've edited.

The file "sunhokey_belt_clip.stl" is designed to fit the Sunhokey 2015 bed, so it can be used with the printer. It has built-in support. Just use a razor blade to separate it. It should pop off.

Equipment Needed:
3D printer
x4 of #6 3/4 inch long screws
x6 of #6 1/2 inch long screws
padding
velcro
rubber bands
x2 of #8 screwable hooks
drum sticks

Note: The equipment needed above is only good for one arm. If two Drum Stick Prosthetics are needed for two arms, more of the equipment above will be needed. Also, the exploded view is not up to date with the current design. The exploded view is included only for reference.

Steps to Build the Drum Stick Prosthetic for Bicep and Forearm

  1. Print out all of the parts:
    x2 Spacers
    x2 Rings
    x1 Rotator_Base
    x1 Rod
    x1 Forearm_Cuff (Make sure to print this using a thermoformable filament)
    x1 Bicep_Cuff (Make sure to print this using a thermoformable filament)
    x2 Base Connectors

  2. Sand off the Formarm_Cuff and Bicep_Cuff to make sure they have a smooth finish.

  3. Attach the Rotator_Base to the 2 Base_Connectors by placing the 2 Base_Connectors on each side of the Rotator_Base, setting a specified angle between the two respective parts, and finally attaching them together by using 4 of the #6 3/4 inch long screws (2 screws per Base_Connector). (See main picture for placement).

  4. Thermoform the Forearm_Cuff to the person's forearm, but make sure that the holes on the top can line up with their respective holes on the 2 Base_Connectors.

  5. Attach the Forearm_Cuff to the Rotator_Base using 4 of the #6 1/2 inch long screws.

  6. Thermoform the Bicep_Cuff to the person's bicep, but make sure that the holes on the side of the Bicep_Cuff line up with their respective holes on the Forearm_Cuff. (See exploded view picture for placement)

  7. Using 2 of the Rings, line each one up on each side of the holes of the Forearm_Cuff and Bicep _Cuff. Using 2 of the #6 1/2 inch long screws, attach the screws through the holes of the Forearm_Cuff and Bicep_Cuff and into the 2 Spacers that should be placed on the inner lining of the Bicep_Cuff. This step will attach the Bicep_Cuff and Forearm_Cuff together. (See exploded view picture and main picture for placement)

  8. Drill a hole in a drum stick that aligns with the holes on the sides of the Rotator_Base farthest from the Forearm_Cuff. Make sure this hole is big enough so that the Rod can fit through it. Next, saw off the back end of the drum stick and then drill a hole in the newly made flat end so that 1 of the #8 screwable hooks can screw into it. (See main picture for placement)

  9. Screw in the other #8 screwable hook into its respective hole in the Rotator_Base. (See main picture for placement)

  10. Attach the drum stick to the Rotator Base by inserting the Rod through the hole in the drum stick and then, using 2 of the #6 1/2 inch long screws, attach the drumstick by inserting these screws from the outside of the Rotator_Base and into the holes of the Rod.

  11. Next, attach a rubber band between the two #8 screwable hooks.

  12. Place padding onto the inner linings of both the Bicep_Cuff and Forearm_Cuff. Cut holes in the lining so that velcro can go through the holes made in these cuffs.

  13. Place velcro through these cuffs to attach onto the person.

  14. Enjoy playing the drums :)

Steps to Build the Drum Stick Prosthetic for Bicep Only

  1. Print out all of the parts:
    x1 Rotator_Base
    x1 Rod
    x1 Arm_Cuff (Make sure to print this using a thermoformable filament)
    x2 Base Connectors

  2. Sand off the Arm_Cuff to make sure it has a smooth finish.

  3. Attach the Rotator_Base to the 2 Base_Connectors by placing the 2 Base_Connectors on each side of the Rotator_Base, setting a specified angle between the two respective parts, and finally attaching them together by using 4 of the #6 3/4 inch long screws (2 screws per Base_Connector). (See main picture for placement).

  4. Thermoform the Arm_Cuff to the person's bicep, but make sure that the holes on the top can line up with their respective holes on the 2 Base_Connectors.

  5. Attach the Arm_Cuff to the Rotator_Base using 4 of the #6 1/2 inch long screws.

  6. Drill a hole in a drum stick that aligns with the holes on the sides of the Rotator_Base farthest from the Forearm_Cuff. Make sure this hole is big enough so that the Rod can fit through it. Next, saw off the back end of the drum stick and then drill a hole in the newly made flat end so that 1 of the #8 screwable hooks can screw into it.

  7. Screw in the other #8 screwable hook into its respective hole in the Rotator_Base. (See main picture for placement)

  8. Attach the drum stick to the Rotator Base by inserting the Rod through the hole in the drum stick and then, using 2 of the #6 1/2 inch long screws, attach the drumstick by inserting these screws from the outside of the Rotator_Base and into the holes of the Rod.

  9. Next, attach a rubber band between the two #8 screwable hooks.

  10. Place padding onto the inner linings of the Arm_Cuff. Cut holes in the lining so that velcro can go through the holes made in this cuff.

  11. Place velcro through the Arm_Cuff to attach onto the person.

  12. Enjoy playing the drums :)

title: Dual 40mm clip-on fan holder for Ultimaker

description.text:
This is a fan holder I made with three objectives in mind:

  • Two open fans. I'm not a huge fan of fan ducts. Some work really well, but having the mouth too close to the nozzle makes it hard to do maintenance on the hot end.

  • 40mm fans. Those are much easier to find than the stock 50mm fans.

  • No nuts or bolts (except for those holding the fans). I've tried too many fan ducts and holders, and switching them was a major pain, so I made this clip-on version that just snaps onto the existing bolts. I hope this encourages people to try this design. :)
    • Inspired by scottvader's good results here:
    http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:125244 I'm insulating with Teflon tape for the time being, but MadOverlord's silicone sock should work wonders:
    http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:165750 2013/12/08 update: The original model could hit the lower bolt on the Y axis sliding block in some cases. That's now fixed!

It shouldn't be hard to print. There's a bridge, but a simple support or printing slowly should take care of that.  
I used 0.2mm layers, 1.2mm walls and 35% infill, but there's not a lot of infill to do anyway.  
I used PLA, and it hasn't sagged or deformed so far. Let me know if you find any issues with it.
